{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474212"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:18:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:18:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11844"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11844"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.52,0.22,0.03,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4445"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106981"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4445"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11844"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89444"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"884"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6414"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35883"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39613"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106981"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his mother crying and refusing to open his eyes. On further questioning, the mother tells you that earlier that day he was playing with wooden sticks with his siblings but she is unsure if anything hit his eye.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with vital signs within normal limits. After instilling anaesthetic drops, a large 4x5 mm central lesion that stains with fluorescein dye is visualised in the left eye. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lubricating eye drops","Antibiotic eye ointment","Patch the eye continuously for one week","Reassurance","Prednisolone drops"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a typical scenario for corneal abrasion, especially in the paediatric population. The most reliable way to diagnose corneal abrasion, particularly in a child who is likely to be resisting examination, is to use fluorescein dye that stains the exposed basement membrane of the corneal epithelium. Abrasions heal relatively quickly (within two to three days), however it is important to use prophylactic antibiotics until the epithelium is completely healed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibiotic eye ointment\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. For this large defect (\u0026gt;2 mm), chloramphenicol 1% ointment with double eye-pad overnight would be appropriate, whilst smaller defects (\u0026lt;2 mm) would be treated with chloramphenicol 0.5% drops four times per day for five to seven days. The advantage of ointment is longer duration of action, though it may cause blurring of vision. A compromise approach uses drops during the day and ointment at bedtime. Patients should be reviewed if pain worsens or persists beyond two to three days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELubricating eye drops\u003C/strong\u003E alone are insufficient for an injured cornea, particularly when organic material may be involved. While lubricants may provide comfort, they do not address the risk of secondary bacterial infection. Follow-up would be necessary much sooner than one week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatching\u003C/strong\u003E continuously for an extended period without antibiotic treatment is not recommended. Prolonged patching may increase infection risk and is particularly concerning in young children who are prone to amblyopia. Modern practice generally avoids routine patching for simple corneal abrasions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone drops\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated in acute corneal abrasions. Corticosteroids may impair healing and increase the risk of infection, particularly when there is potential contamination from organic material.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be inadequate given the size and central location of this corneal abrasion, which requires active treatment to prevent complications and ensure proper healing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Corneal abrasions require topical antibiotics prophylaxis and follow up.","Fluorescein staining is the most reliable method to diagnose corneal abrasions, particularly in children.","Large corneal abrasions (\u003E2 mm) should be treated with antibiotic ointment rather than drops due to longer duration of action."],"references":["Royal Children\u2019s Hospital Melbourne. Acute eye injury. In: Clinical Practice Guidelines. Parkville, Vic: Royal Children\u2019s Hospital; 2022 Dec. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Acute_eye_injury/","Agency for Clinical Innovation (NSW). Eye Emergency Manual, 3rd ed. Sydney. Available at: https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0013/155011/ACI-Eye-Emergency-Manual.pdf","Heath Jeffrey RC, Dobes J, Chen FK. Eye injuries. Aust J Gen Prac 2022; 51:476-82"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89444"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11844"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89444","links":{